{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_kendall_ver01/data/sn82014085/00393346814/1945081701/0559.xml":{"full_text":"The Weather\nContinued Clear\nFull Weather Report hfi t\n\u00bbEs Mwmg Demokrat\n(PubUahed Iraj Branlnt it M Oread Street Waterbary. Altered m Second Ota* Metier M Poet Office et Weterturj, Ooan Under the Act of Much s, 1879)\nESTABLISHED 1881 VOL LXffl. NO. 188\nTOE WATERBURY\n\u00bba\nMT\u00bb WATERBURY. CONN., FRIDAY, AUGUST 17, 1945\nSIXTEEN PAGES\nPRICE 4\nPrefers Quiet Celebrations\nThe noise end the excitement of the Jsp surrender celebration In\nNew York's Chinatown prosed too much for two-year-rid Fred Chang,\nthe forlorn little flgore with flag and ben above, Fred is the son of\nan American soldier.\nReds Seek Land\nIn North China\nWifi Likely \"Soft\nPedal\" Communist\nIssue for Gain*\nCalcutta, Aug. 17 (UP) In\nformed persona arriving from\nChungking believe that Soviet Rus\nsia has agreed to \u201csoft pedal\u201d the\nChinese Communist issue in return\nfor considerable territorial and\neconomic concessions in North\nChina.\nThe terms are believed to involve\nthree Chinese consesslons:\n1. Chinese have agreed to a free\nport for the Russians at Port Ar\nthur.\n2. China is ceding to Russia the\nstrategic Tanu Tavu area on the\nborder of Outer Mongolia and Si\nberia, and giving the Soviets a free\nhand in Outer Mongolia.\n3. Considerable concessions have\nbeen made in the long disputed\nSianklang area where the central\ngovernment recently replaced the\npro-Soviet governor with a die\nhard Chlang Kai-shek follower.\nThese sources believed that China\nhas retained inner Mongolia and ob\ntained control of Manchuria, with\nout China cannot become an indus\ntrial power.\nIt is thought that Russia agreed\nChinese control in Manchuria to\n(Continued on Page 4)\nPost-war Tax\nUndisclosed\nBy JOHN L. CUTTER\n(United Frees Staff Correspondent)\nWashington, Aug. 7\u2014(UP)\u2014Pres\nident Truman maintained silence\non the nature of his postwar tax\nrecommendations today, but mem\nbers of Congress talked about re\nlief for both business and individ\nuals.\nAll signs Indicate that some tax\nrelief may be expected effective next\nyear. It probably will be many years,\nhowever, before taxes on both bus\niness and Individuals drop far from\ntheir record wartime levels.\nPreparing Laws\nMr. Truman told a news confer\nence yesterday that experts were\nnow working on legislation for post\nwar tax adjustments, but added that\nhe^ could say nothing more for the\nThe first tax relief for individuals\nmight be through elimination of the\n(Continued on Page 4)\nTodoy't lnd\u00abx\nPage Page\nAmusements it 19\nBob Bops 7 Obituaries t\nOr. Brady 10 Dan Parker it\nCIO Seeks\nPay Boosts\nFor Workers\nLittle Steel Formula\nAffected; WLB\nContinued\nBy CHARLES H. HERROLD\n(United Press Staff Correspondent)\nWashington, Aug. 17\u2014(UP)\u2014The\nCongress of Industrial Organiza\ntions opened Labor\u2019s drive today to\nobtain pay boosts under the gov\nernment\u2019s newly liberalized wage\npolicy.\nPresident Truman announced yes\nterday that the War Labor Board\nwill be allowed during the recon\nversion period to permit all volun\ntary wage Increases which are not\nunstabMHng and to order such\nraises as are necessary to \u201ceffective\"\nreconversion.\nBreak Formula\nThe president is now drafting an\nexecutive order to this effect. It will\nclear the way for the WLB to break,\ndiscard or Ignore the Little Steel\nFormula, which held wartime wage\nIncreases to 15 percent above Jan\nuary, 1941, levels.\nOIO President Philip Murray dis\nclosed that all CIO unions will ask\nemployers for collective bargaining\nconferences to negotiate higher\nwages in the light of the president\u2019s\nnew policy. Most CIO unions have\na clause In their contract permitlng\nreopening the question of wages If\nthe national policy changes.\nMurray also indicates CHO\u2019s will\ningness to continue Its no-strlke\npolicy during reconversion. He said\n(Continued on Page 4)\nPeace-Production\nWork Speeded-Up\nCurtail Federal\nControls to Aid\nI ndustry-Workers\nBy SANDOB 8. KLEIN\n(United Press Staff Correspondent)\nWashington, Aug. 17\n(UP)\u2014Government agencies\nare following up their mass\nwar contract cancellations\nwith a program for speedy\nclearance of plants so that\nindustry can get tooled up\nand stocked up without de\nlay for peacetime production,\nit was learned today.\nA high-ranking War Production\nBoard official said that If any re\nconverting Industry is Impeded by\ngovernment delay In plant clear\nances, the WPB Is ready to \u201cnudge\u201d\nthe offending agency.\nClearances Effected\nSo far the WPB has had only a\nvery few complaints. The officials\nsaid that both the army and navy\nhave done a \u201cfairly adequate job\"\non clearances from former war\nplants and the army air forces\nhave dime an especially outstanding\nJob.\nA necessary prelude to plant\nclearance Is contract settlement.\nFrequently, contractors desire gov\nernment-owned equipment and some\nof the materials on hand In their\nplants when a contract Is cancelled.\nIn these cases, the contractors pre\nfer to have such Inventories left on\ntheir premises. Contract settlements\ntake this In consideration.\nIn other cases, the contractors\nmay ask the government to move\nout materials and equipment. If the\ngovernment falls to do so In 60 days,\nthe contractor may do so at govern\nment expense. However, contractors\nmay move or store Inventories at\ntheir own expense If they want It\ndone before the government can get\naround to It within the 60 day\nRevoke WPB Controls\nHie War Production Board put\nthe finishing touches today to docu\nments revoking almost 960 WPB\norders controlling Industry. Most of\nthe orders that will be lifted by\nnext week-end Involve limitations\non production and distribution.\nSome 40 being retained govern in\n(Continued on Page 3)\nNew Bomber\nHas World\nWide Range\nWashington, Aug. 17\u2014(UP)\u2014Gen.\nHenry H. Arnold today revealed ex\nistence of a new army super-bomber\nwith a range two and one-half to\nthree times greater than the B-29.\nHe said it would cover all of Asia,\nthe Pacific and the Atlantic from\npresent U. S. bases. The new bomb\ner has not been named.\nThe commanding general of the\nair forces said the army also has\nrockets that will be drawn auto\nmatically to a target by the pres\nence of heat, light or metal in the\nHe said these weapons, coupled\nwith the atomic bomb, have brought\nthe \u201cBuck Rogers\" conception of\nair power into reality.\nFuture security of the United\nStates and the peace of the world\ndepends on air superiority resulting\nfrom progressive research aided by\nthe country\u2019s scientists and indus\ntries, he continued.\nArnold said the scientists who de\nveloped the atomic bomb showed\nwhat they could do when given\nmoney and facilities.\nNew Rockets\n(Continued on Page 2)\nAcheson Of Connecticut\nNamed State Secretary\nIjrB.IL tntALiuunu\n(United rnw SUIT Comepondent)\nWashington, Aug. 17.\u2014(UP)\u2014Ap\npointment o f Dean O. Aebeeon to be\nthe new undersecretary of state in\ndicated today that a thorough re\norganisation of the U. S. foreign\nservice may be in prospect.\nSecretary of Stale Jamas F.\nByrnes east aside a generally fol\nlowed custom when he selected the\nM-year-old Acheeon to be his No.\n1 assistant in the oonduct of for\neign affairs.\nGovernor\nConfident\nOf Future\nImmediate Plant\nFor New England\nBegins Monday\nHartford, Conn., Aug. 17\u2014(UP)\u2014\nBack from a reconversion confer\nence with President Truman and\nthe governors of seven other states.\nGov. Baldwin declared today that\nConnecticut, and the country on a\nwhole, \u201cstands on the threshold of\na new era, an era filled with tre\nmendous possibilities for our pro\ngress and welfare.\u201d\nImmediate Solution\nImmediate postwar problems, he\nsaid, would be taken up at a meet\ning of New England governors Mon\nday at Boston.\nThe governor\u2019s expression, of op\ntimism came as the state\u2019s indus\ntries resumed operations after a\ntwo-day victory holiday. Many\nplants, however, especially the larg\ner ones, announced they would re\nmain closed another ten days to\ntake Inventories as result of con\ntract cancellations. Whatever unem\nployment might result was expected\nto be quickly absorbed by a rapid\nchange over to peacetime produc\ntion.\nTo help In this problem, the state\nfinance advisory committee made an\nadditional *4*000 available to the\nConnecticut reemployment commis\nsion to extend Its program for the\nremainder of the year. The program\nIncluded both civilian reemployment\nand veteran placement\nKetam To Sober Thought\nMeanwhile, peace celebration\nsprees were over, stores and banks\nreopened, and the two-day liquor\nholiday was declared ended.\nThe end of rationing of gasoline,\ncanned vegetables and fruits, touch\ned off an unpredecented wave of\nbuying. Merchants reported that\ntheir stocks\u2014especially fruit Juices\n\u2014disappeared <V>mpletely, now that\nthey are point-free. They expected\nthe buying to continue another few\ndays.\nGasoline stations reported a stag\ngering demand for fuel. Although\nthere was plenty of gasoline, distri\nbutors predicted It would be from\nthree days to a week before their\ndelivery schedules could be revised.\nA tremendous Increase In highway\ntravel was reported.\nEmployment\nOutlook Good\nNew York, Aug. 17.\u2014(UP)\u2014Ira\nMosher, president of the National\nAssociation of Manufacturers, said\ntoday that an NAM survey Indicated\nthat fewer than 1,500,000 industrial\nworkers would be unemployed dur\ning the reconversion period.\nMost of these might be re-employ\ned within three months from the\nstart of the reconversion period,\nMosher said the survey Indicated.\nWidespread Survey\nThe survey was made among 1,700\nof the NAM\u2019s 13,000 members.\n\u201cEven at that period of recon\nversion when the most people are\nout of work, employment In manu\nfacturing will not drop below that\nof 1909,\u201d Mosher said.\nMosher said yesterday that the\nsurvey Indicated that 01 per cent\nof the U. S. manufacturing firms\nfaced no re-conversion delays. The\nsurvey showed, he said, that only\n11 per cent of the manufacturers\nwould require more than 30 days\nto switch to peacetime production.\nFIREMAN\u2019S HOLIDAY\nBecket, Mass., Aug. 17\u2014(UP)\u2014\nBelatedly celebrating the surrender\nof Japan. Fire Chief George J.\nCrochierre obtained permission from\nMrs. Julia Barber to burn hte ruins\nof her house which was destroyed\npartially by fire a few weeks ago.\nN. H. Firemen\nAwarded\nNew Haven, Aag. 17\u2014A\n\u2022pedal two-day leave with pay\nhas been granted every mem\nber of the New Haven Fire\nDepartment by Mayor John\nW. Morphy In recognition of\ntheir efficient dnty during the\nElm Cltyje two-snd-a-iuUI day\nof the Japanese.\nDemands Emissaries Arriv\n\u201cWithout Further Delay\u201d\nEmperor Orders \u201cCease-Fire\nWait For Job Instructions\nPart of the orderly, good-natured crowd of Waterbary war-worker*, laid off this morale\nV. 8. Employment office, Bank itreet, for Instruction* and advice as to future\nTo Lay-Off 10,000\nWithin Ten Days\nWartime Workers\nHit By Federal Re\nconversion Direc\ntives; Factories Pre\npare for Postwar\nWork\nBy ANNE ZEMAITIS\nUnemployment and recon\nversion came into the Water\nbury industrial picture with\nwide sweeps today, as thou\nsands of workers were sent\nhome upon reporting for em\nployment following the two\nday Victory holiday.\nA direct aftermath of the\ncancellation of Army Ord\nnance contracts, the unem\nployment load is expected to\nreach more than 10,000 be\nfore the end of next week\n\u2014about a quarter of the\ncity\u2019s industrial workers.\nU.S.E.S. Busy\nThe most vivid evidence of the\n\u201creconversion holiday\u201d was noted\non Bank street, where hundreds\nof persons waited in line to gain\nentrance to the U.S. Employment\nService for filing of unemployment\nclaims and job requests. Company\nofficials meanwhile issued state\n(Continued on Page 4)\nMore Japs\nSan Francisco, Aug. 17.\u2014(UP)\u2014\nVice Admiral Takijiro Onlshi, chief\nof the naval general staff who is\ncredited by Tokyo with having orig\ninated Japan\u2019s suicide air force,\nhas followed the Japanese war min\nister in committing hari-kari to\natone for his nations\u2019 defeat.\nThe official Japanese news agency\nreported he took his life at 3 a. m.\nyesterday in his official residence\nafter leaving a note addressed \u2018To\nthe ufpirits of the members of the\nspecial attacks corps\u2019\u2019 which said:\nStatement\n\u201cEver convinced of final victory,\nyou fell gallantly as human bullets\nBut that conviction finally hasn't\nbeen fulfilled. With my death. I as\npire to make atonement for all you\n-of the be\ncandidates and members\nreeved.\u201d\nOnlshi's suicide followed by less\nthan 46 hours that of War Min\nuter Oen Korechlka Anaml. Thus\nboth the Japanese Army and Navy\nhave \u201catoned\" for their failure to\nwin the war for Emperor Hirohito.\neted that\nhave been elevated to\nControversy\nOn Post-War\nDraft\nCongress-Truman\nConflict Said\nTo Be Coming\nBY DEAN W. DITTMER\nUnited Press Staff Correspondent\nWashington, Aug. 17\u2014(UP)\u2014Con\ngressional sources predicted today\nthat Pesldent Truman and Congress\nwill have their first major clash\nover continued drafting of men for\nthe army.\nMr. Truman has ordered continu\ned Induction of 50000 men a month.\nCompared with the recent rate of\n80,000.\nWant Draft Ended\nSenate and House military affairs\ncommittee leaders have expressed\na desire to stop inductions Immedi\nately. But the President said yester\nday that \u201cthere isnt any reason why\nsome of these young men who\narent doing anything right now\nshouldnt relieve the men at the\nfront so they can return.\u2019\u2019\nHe said the draft would be con\ntinued until replacements are suffi\ncient to send veterans home from\nthe occupation fronts.\nHis added remark that congress\nmust decide how long the draft will\noperate, indicated that some form\nof compromise may be In the sir.\nJust before a 30-minute confer\nence with Mr. Truman this week\nchairman Andrew J. May, D., Ky.,\nof the House Military Affairs Oom\n(Continued on Page 4)\nJob Layoffs\nAccepted\nCalmly\nDemocrat's CKecK\nReveals War\nWorkers as Hopeful\nBy BETTY BLANCHARD\nLittle discouragement or pessim\nism was reflected by the hundreds\nof war workers who waited this\nmorning to file unemployment\nclaims on the sidewalk before the\nU. a Employment Service, 123\nBank street.\nThere were no long faces nor hang\ndog expressions on the faces of\npeople who laughed and chided one\nanother during the long wait. All\nasserted they were too happy about\nthe end of the war to be much dis\nturbed. The reconversion period\nwould extend, they felt, from three\nto six months, but after that they\nlooked forward to years of prosper\nity and happiness.\nThe worries they expressed for\n(Continued on Page 2)\nPleasant\nWeek-End\nBoston, Aug. 17\u2014(UP)\u2014New Eng\nland extended weather forecast:\nPleasant weather with comforta\nble temperatures during the next\nfive days with temperatures aver\naging a few degrees below the sea\nsonal normal.\nSomewhat warmer weather Sat\nurday and Sunday will be followed\nby cooler weather again during the\nearly part of next week.\nNormal temperatures tor the peri\no din elude Boston 60 degrees; New\nHaven, Conn., and Providence, R. L,\n70; Nantucket, 68; Concord, N. H.,\nand Portland, Me., 68; Burlington\nVt., 67; Eastport, Me., 61; Green\nville, Me., 62, and Presque Isle, Me.,\n63.\nPoland Relinquishes 47%\nOf Territory To Russia\nBy BRUCE MUNN\nUnited Frees Staff Correspondent\nLondon. Aug. 17\u2014(UP)\u2014Observ\ners estimated today that Poland will\ngive up 71.900 square miles\u201447 per\ncent of her pre-war boundary and\ndetermining the sharing of Oerman\nreparations.\nSoviet Foreign Minister V. M\nMolotov and Polish Premier Eduard\nOsubka-Morawskl signed the new\nagreement last night, radio Moscow\nreported.\nPoland Gets Part of Germany\nIn return for territory oeded tc\nRussia, Poland will receive a large\nallee of Oermany. The Big Threi\nat Potsdam recommended that Pol*\nand receive approximately two*\nthirds of Bast Pruaaia and that Uu\nsions, which considered western\nboundaries, agreed on a mutual\nfrontier based on the Ouraon line\nbut deviating from that line in Pol\nand\u2019s favor In some districts from\nthree to five miles.\n1.\u2014A territory east\nvar up to\nThe\nMost of Jop A\nPrepares to 1\nDown Arms;\ning Contin\nMany Sect)\nBULLET\nSan Francisco,\n(UP)\u2014A Japanese\ncast beamed to Gen. Doug\nlas MacArthur\u2019s headquar\nters said today that TdM\nsurrender emissaries affl\nfly to Manila Sunday.\nBy RALPH TEATSOBTH\n(United Pren Staff\nManila, Aug. 17\u2014(\nGen. Douglas Mae\ntold Japan today to\nstalling and to send si\nder emissaries to hia _\nquartern at Manila for\nrender terms \u201cwithout\nther delay.\u201d\nThe Supreme Allied\npation commander, pi\nirritated over Japanese j\nering, brusquely\nTogo\u2019s request tor\ncation of the duties\nManila miartOP,\n\u201cYour assumption\nthe tasks of the J\nsentatives to leant\nMaoArthirr informed\neral Headquarters by radio.\n\"The directive tram this\nquarters la clear and\nto be complied with\nther delay.\"\nDeieyed_\nThe mission originally\nhave flown to Manu*\nMacArthur granted the\nmore time to complete\nmeats for the flight. HU\nrectlves had specified that\nslon was only to receive tte j\nterms and take them to f\nor, the Imperial general\ntors and the govemme\nsign them.\nRadio Tokyo, meanwhile,\nthat Hlrohlto had\ncease-fire order\n(Continued on\nB-29 Pilots\nGallant Sa<\n(Continued on\nTHtt ACCIX\nSPOILS#\nCAJSmA","height":"28388","width":"20652"}}
